title: GCSE results (‘Attainment 8’) for children aged 14 to 16 (key stage 4)
measure_summary:
This data measures how children perform in exams for 8 GCSE-level qualifications, referred to by the Department of Education (DfE) as ‘Attainment 8’.

The data covers the academic year 2015/16 (September 2015 to July 2016).

Attainment 8 is one of 2 important new ways of measuring how well children do in key stage 4 (years 10 and 11, when pupils are aged between 14 and 16). The other is ‘Progress 8’. These measures were first implemented by the DfE in 2016.

The 8 subjects which make up Attainment 8 include English and Maths, which are both ‘double-weighted’, meaning they are given twice the importance of other subjects.

Of the remaining 6 subjects, 3 must come from qualifications that go towards the English Baccalaureate (EBacc), and 3 can be either EBacc subjects, GCSE subjects, or technical qualifications from [a list approved by the Department of Education](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/2018-performance-tables-discount-codes)
 
Each individual grade a pupil achieves is assigned a point score, which is then used to calculate their total ‘Attainment 8’ score. 

To calculate the national average for Attainment 8, DfE adds together all the ‘Attainment 8’ scores given to individual children, and divides them by the total number of pupils in key stage 4.
summary:
* in 2015/16, there were 540,689 pupils in key stage 4 at maintained schools in England, with ethnicity known for 534,918 (99%)

* 79% were White, 10% were Asian, 5% were Black, 4% were Mixed race, 1.5% came from the Other ethnic group and 0.4% were Chinese

* Chinese and Asian pupils on average scored higher than the national average for Attainment 8

* White pupils, Mixed race pupils and Black pupils scored at or just below the national average for Attainment 8

* Gypsy, Traveller or Irish Traveller pupils had the lowest average score for Attainment 8
need_to_know:
Caution should be used when comparing results based on small numbers of pupils.

Attainment is lower for children from a Traveller of Irish heritage background – however, there were only 122 pupils from this background in key stage 4 in 2015/16. This was a much smaller number than for other ethnic groups (for example, there were 20,434 Pakistani pupils in key stage 4). Therefore, data comparisons between Traveller of Irish Heritage pupils and other ethnic groups may be unreliable.
Ethnicity was not supplied for 1.1% of pupils at the end of key stage 4 (5,771 pupils). This includes pupils for whom ethnicity was not collected or could not be determined, and pupils who refused to give their ethnicity.

In the published ‘statistical first release’ (SFR) for Attainment 8 (key stage 4) and related data, the DfE has ‘suppressed’ very small numbers (for example, values of 1 or 2, a percentage based on 1 or 2 pupils who achieved, or 0, 1 or 2 pupils who did not achieve a particular level). ‘Suppression’ means these figures have not been included in the data, because the numbers involved are too small to draw any meaningful conclusions.

Where the size of the ethnic group population is small enough that an individual’s identity could come to light, some other figures have also been excluded. This type of exclusion, also called ‘suppression’ of data, is consistent with DfE’s statistical policy statement on confidentiality.

The Attainment 8 measure only includes qualifications which count towards the secondary performance tables. 

Schools that offer unapproved qualifications, such as unregulated international GCSEs, will not have these qualifications counted in the performance tables. Achievements in these qualifications by pupils at such schools are not reflected in this data. 

This data therefore represents the performance of schools and pupils in qualifications which count in the performance tables, rather than all qualifications taken by pupils. The difference between the figures for all schools and state-funded schools is mostly due to the impact of the unregulated international GCSEs taken in independent schools. 

Data for pupil attainment analysed according to the religious character of a school is only provided for faith schools and schools of no religious character which are funded by the state. Additionally, data for some Muslim and Sikh schools was not included in these statistics, because the small numbers of pupils make it impossible to draw meaningful conclusions about their attainment.
ethnicity_definition_summary:
This data uses categories from the Department of Education’s school census, which is broadly based on the 2001 national census, with 2 exceptions:  

* Traveller of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma children have been separated into 2 categories
* Sri Lankan has been added to the Asian/Asian British group

These small changes were made after consultations with local authorities and lobby groups. 

The categories are as follows:

White:

* White British
* White Irish
* Traveller of Irish Heritage
* Gypsy/Roma
* Other White

Mixed/Multiple ethnic groups:

* White and Black Caribbean
* White and Black African
* White and Asian
* Other Mixed background

Asian/Asian British:

* Indian
* Pakistani
* Bangladeshi
* Sri Lankan
* Other Asian Background

Black/African/Caribbean/Black British:

* Black African
* Black Caribbean
* Other Black background

Other ethnic group:

* Chinese
* Other Background
* Unknown

Information about Attainment 8 is provided for both specific and broad ethnic categories, with the exception of data for local authority, school type, school admission, religious character and special educational needs. Here, it is only provided for the 5 broad ethnic groups, to preserve confidentiality and ensure individuals cannot be identified. For more information about suppression of this data, please see the Methodology section.

Here, the school census replaces ‘Other ethnic group’ with ‘Chinese’, again after consultations with local authorities and lobby groups.

The 5 broad categories are as follows:

* White
* Mixed/Multiple ethnic groups
* Asian/Asian British
* Black/African/Caribbean/Black British
* Chinese
data_source_purpose: The primary purpose is to measure schools and pupil performance at key stage 4 (GCSE) to monitor and improve standards and inform parental choice.
methodology:
The key stage 4 datasets are compiled using information matched together from 3 data sources:

* prior attainment records (key stage 2 results) 
* school census records 
* qualification entries and results collected from awarding bodies 

Key stage 4 data received from awarding bodies is combined with pupil characteristics from the school census and prior attainment by the department’s contractor. 

Records are matched, using identifiers such as surname, forename, date of birth, unique pupil number (UPN), gender and postcode. This successfully matches around 98% of results. 

The statistics in this commission cover the data collated for the 2016 secondary school performance tables. The performance tables and the related statistical first release report results are based on pupils at the end of key stage 4, who are typically aged 15 at the start of the academic year. 

Local authority (LA) and regional statistics only cover state-funded schools in England. This includes city technology colleges and academies but excludes hospital schools, pupil referral units and alternative provision.

Pupils are included in the figures for FSM if their families have claimed eligibility for FSM at the time of the annual spring school census. This FSM definition includes all who were eligible to receive free school meals, not only those who actually received free school meals. Pupils not eligible for free school meals or unclassified pupils are described as ‘All other pupils’.                  

Parents are able to claim FSM if they receive a qualifying benefit. The list is currently:

* Income Support
* Income-based Jobseeker's Allowance
* Income-related Employment and Support Allowance
* support under Part VI of the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999
* the Guarantee element of State Pension Credit Child Tax Credit, provided they are not entitled to Working Tax Credit and have an annual gross income that does not exceed £16,190, as assessed by HM Revenue & Customs
* where a parent is entitled to the Working Tax Credit run on – the payment someone receives for a further 4 weeks after they stop qualifying for Working Tax Credit those on Universal Credit
* children who receive an eligible benefit in their own right

FSM is used as an indicator of disadvantage, but when drawing conclusions, it should be remembered that not all eligible parents apply for FSM and families who don’t quite reach the eligibility threshold for FSM may still be suffering deprivation.
disclosure_control:
The DfE preserves confidentiality. The Code of Practice for Official Statistics requires us to take reasonable steps to ensure that our published or disseminated statistics protect confidentiality.

Values of 1 or 2, or a percentage based on 1 or 2 pupils who achieved; or 0, 1 or 2 pupils who did not achieve a particular level are suppressed in circumstances where non-suppression would lead to disclosure of pupils.  Some additional figures have been suppressed to prevent the possibility of a suppressed figure being revealed. 

This suppression is consistent with our Statistical policy statement on confidentiality.

Schools are able to apply for pupils to be removed from their figures, if they have recently arrived from overseas and their first language is not English. We allow the removal of these pupils from the school and local authority figures as they can have an impact on some schools’ figures (since some schools have significant numbers of such pupils). However, we continue to include these pupils in the national figures so that they reflect the attainment of all pupils. 

Schools can also apply for pupils to be removed if a pupil has been admitted following a permanent exclusion from another school, if the pupil is not at the end of key stage 4, if the pupil has permanently left England, or the pupil is deceased. 

It may not be appropriate for schools to be held accountable for these pupils and therefore with adequate evidence we allow the removal of them so they are not included in their performance measures.
estimation: Percentages and average Attainment 8 scores are given to one decimal place.

dimensions.title: GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) by ethnicity
dimensions.summary:
This data shows that:

* the average Attainment 8 score for all pupils in both state-funded mainstream and special schools was 50

* looking at the broad ethnic categories, Chinese pupils scored an average of 62 and Asian pupils an average of 52, both higher than the national average for Attainment 8 

* White and Mixed race pupils scored an average of 50 and Black pupils scored an average of 49 

* looking at the specific ethnic minority categories, Indian pupils scored an average of 57, and Traveller of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma children had the lowest average score, at 20
dimensions.source: Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2015 to 2016

dimensions.title: GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) by ethnicity and eligibility for free school meals (FSM)
dimensions.summary:
Eligibility for FSM is used as an indicator of deprivation by the Department of Education. For more about who qualifies for FSM, see the Methodology section. 

This data shows that:

* 13% of pupils (72,528 children) in key stage 4 were eligible for free school meals (FSM) in 2015/16

* 25% of pupils from the Other ethnic background, 23% of Black pupils, 19% of pupils from a Mixed race background, 18% of Asian pupils, 12% of White pupils and 6% of Chinese pupils were eligible for FSM

* pupils eligible for FSM had an average Attainment 8 score of 39, which is 13 points lower than the average for all other children

* the average score was lower for pupils eligible for FSM across all ethnicities, with the exception of Gypsy/Roma and Traveller of Irish Heritage children, where there was little difference between those eligible and those not eligible
                                                                                                                                                  
* Chinese pupils eligible for FSM had the highest score (59) in this group of pupils, and White pupils eligible for FSM the lowest (37)

* White Irish pupils saw the biggest gap between the 2 groups, at 17 points, with FSM-eligible pupils scoring an average of 40 and those non-eligible scoring 57

* use caution with this data: the statistics quoted here for some ethnic groups are based on very small numbers of pupils (for example, only 130 Chinese children were eligible for FSM in 2015/16) and are highly variable over time
dimensions.source: Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2015 to 2016

dimensions.title: GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) by ethnicity and area
dimensions.summary:
This data shows that:

* Sutton has the highest average Attainment 8 score (59) and Knowsley the lowest (39)

* the average score for Attainment 8 was lower in the Midlands and northern parts of the country than in the south of England and London 

* White pupils achieved their highest average score in Westminster (58)

* Mixed pupils pupils achieved their highest average score in Kingston-Upon-Thames (61)

* Asian pupils pupils achieved their highest average score in York (70)

* Black pupils pupils achieved their highest average score in Southend-on-Sea (62)

* Chinese pupils pupils achieved their highest average score in Reading (78)

* the lowest scores for Attainment 8 were found in Knowsley (for White pupils), in Sandwell (for Mixed pupils), on the Isle of Wight (for Asian and Chinese pupils), and in South Tyneside (for Black pupils)
dimensions.source: Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2015 to 2016

dimensions.title: GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) by ethnicity and gender
dimensions.summary:
This data shows that:

* average scores for GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) were higher for girls than boys across all ethnic groups in key stage 4  (years 10 and 11, when pupils are aged between 14 and 16)

* girls achieved an average score of 52, which is 5 points higher than the average score of boys

* Chinese girls achieved the highest average score, at 65

* Boys from a Gypsy/Roma and Traveller of Irish heritage background had the lowest average score, at 19

* the smallest difference in scores between girls and boys was found among pupils from a Gypsy/Roma and Traveller of Irish Heritage background, where girls scored an average of 3 points more than boys

* the largest difference in scores between girls and boys was found among pupils from the Other Black background, where girls scored an average of 7 points more than boys
dimensions.source: Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2015 to 2016

dimensions.title: GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) by ethnicity, gender and eligibility for free school meals (FSM)
dimensions.summary:
Eligibility for FSM is used as an indicator of deprivation by the Department of Education. For more about who qualifies for FSM, see the Methodology section.

This data shows that:

* girls eligible for FSM scored an average of 5 points more for Attainment 8 than boys eligible for FSM across all ethnic groups 

* White British FSM-eligible boys scored an average of 16 points less than White British non-eligible boys; for White British girls the gap was 15 points

* within the broad ethnic categories, FSM-eligible Chinese girls had the highest average Attainment 8 score and FSM-eligible White boys the lowest  

* Gypsy/Roma boys who were eligible for FSM had the lowest average score

* Chinese girls who were not eligible for FSM had the highest average score

* Black Caribbean pupils eligible for FSM showed the biggest difference in average score between girls and boys, with girls scoring an average of 8 points more 

* the smallest difference in average score between girls and boys was found among Bangladeshi pupils eligible for FSM, with girls scoring 3 points more

* pupils from a Traveller of Irish Heritage background also showed very little difference in average score between girls and boys who were eligible for FSM, but this finding was based on very small numbers (41 boys and 32 girls), making it hard to draw any firm conclusions
dimensions.source: Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2015 to 2016

dimensions.title: GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) by ethnicity, gender and area
dimensions.summary:
This data shows that:

* overall, girls had a higher average score for GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) than boys for every local authority apart from the Isles of Scilly

* the biggest gaps in Attainment 8 scores between girls and boys were found for White pupils in Camden (girls scored an average of 9 points more), for Mixed pupils in Rutland (girls scored an average of 16 points more), for Asian pupils on the Isle of Wight (girls scored an average of 27 points more), for Black pupils in South Tyneside (girls scored an average of 32 points more), and for Chinese pupils in Harrow (girls scored an average of 29 points more) 

* use caution with this data: except for the information for White and Mixed race pupils, the statistics quoted here for Attainment 8 achievement by local authority are based on small numbers of pupils and are highly variable over time
dimensions.source: Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2015 to 2016

dimensions.title: GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) by ethnicity, basis for school admission and gender
dimensions.summary:
This data groups schools by type [https://www.gov.uk/types-of-school] into the following 3 categories, according to whether they select their pupils by ability:

* selective schools
* non-selective schools in highly selective areas (where 25% or more of * state-funded secondary places are in state-funded selective schools) 
* all other non-selective schools (including schools in local authorities with some selection, as well as those with no selection)                                                                                                                               

This data shows that:

* in 2015/16, 22,512 pupils in key stage 4 (years 10 and 11, when pupils are aged between 14 and 16) were in selective schools, 34,658 in non-selective schools in highly selective areas, and 472,525 in non-selective schools in other areas

* girls performed better than boys across all types of school and all ethnic groups 

* Chinese girls in selective schools had the highest average score for Attainment 8 (74) and White boys in non-selective schools in highly selective areas had the lowest (45)

* the smallest difference in scores between boys and girls was found among Black pupils in selective schools, where girls scored an average of 0.6 points more than boys

* overall, the biggest difference in scores between boys and girls was found among Black pupils in non-selective schools in highly selective areas, where girls scored an average of 8 points more than boys                                                               

* for White pupils, the biggest gap between girls and boys was found in non-selective schools in non-selective areas, where girls scored an average of 4 points more than boys
dimensions.source: Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2015 to 2016

dimensions.title: GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) by ethnicity, special education needs (SEN) and gender
dimensions.summary:
Pupils with special education needs (SEN) have learning difficulties or disabilities that make it harder for them to learn than most children of the same age. 

From 2015, pupils have been categorised as follows:                                                             

* no identified SEN                                                                                                                           
* SEN support: extra or different help is given from that provided as part of the school's usual curriculum, and the class teacher and SEN coordinator (SENCO) may receive advice or support from outside specialists
* SEN statement or education, health and care (EHC) plan: a pupil is given an SEN statement or an EHC plan once a formal assessment has been made                                                            
 
‘All SEN pupils’ refers to the total number of pupils with either SEN support, an SEN statement or an EHC plan. 

This data shows that:

* in 2015/16, there were 78,682 pupils with special education needs (SEN) in key stage 4  (years 10 and 11, when pupils are aged between 14 and 16)

* of these, 80%  were White, 4% were Mixed race, 7% were Asian, 6% were Black and 0.2% were Chinese

* of the 78,682 SEN pupils in total, 74% had SEN support and 26% had an SEN statement or EHC plan

* looking at all SEN pupils, Chinese pupils had the highest average score for Attainment 8 results (41) and White pupils had the lowest (31) 

* of all SEN pupils, the biggest difference between boys and girls in Attainment 8 achievement, at 7 points, was found among Chinese pupils, where girls scored an average of 46 points and boys an average of 39
dimensions.source: Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2015 to 2016

dimensions.title: GCSE-level exam results (‘Attainment 8’) by ethnicity, religion of school and gender
dimensions.summary:
This data divides schools into the following religious categories:

* no religious character 
* Church of England schools 
* Roman Catholic schools
* Other Christian faith schools (including those of mixed denomination or other Christian beliefs, for example, Greek Orthodox)
* Jewish schools
* Muslim schools
* Sikh schools


The data shows that:

* 530,580 pupils in key stage 4 (years 10 and 11, when pupils are aged between 14 and 16) attended state-funded mainstream schools in 2015/16

* 82% of pupils attended schools with no religious character, 10% attended Roman Catholic schools, 6% attended Church of England schools, 2% attended Other Christian faith schools, 0.2% attended Jewish schools, 0.1% attended Muslim schools, and 0.03% attended Sikh schools

* looking at all ethnicities, pupils at Jewish schools had the highest average score for GCSE-level exams (60) and those at schools with no religious character had the lowest (51)

* Chinese girls at Other Christian faith schools had the highest average score (69) and Black boys at schools with no religious character had the lowest (46.0) 

* White pupils did best at Jewish schools (where they scored an average of 60) and worst at schools with no religious character (where they scored an average of 50)
dimensions.source: Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2015 to 2016
